From c78a82f52bdd6b4749d9daf200227157b720ff81 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Paul Meyer <katexochen0@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Apr 2026 16:28:15 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] Use fd-relative syscalls to avoid intermediate directory
 traversal

In multi-user mode, Guard::drop_privileges() sets the thread's euid
to the FUSE caller before accessing the backing filesystem. This
causes EACCES when intermediate directories on the backing FS path
are not traversable by the caller (e.g. Nix creates root:root 0700
temp dirs, then chowns only the leaf build/ subdirectory).

Replace all path-based syscalls (open, lstat, mkdir, etc.) with
fd-relative equivalents (openat, fstatat, mkdirat, etc.):

1. Walk ancestor path components as root using
   openat(O_PATH|O_NOFOLLOW|O_DIRECTORY) to pin the parent dir.
2. Drop privileges to the FUSE caller.
3. Perform the leaf operation via *at() relative to the pinned fd.

This preserves per-file authorization (the caller still needs
permission on the target file and its immediate parent) while
avoiding spurious failures from inaccessible ancestor directories.

For xattr operations which have no *at() variants, use an O_PATH fd
and operate via /proc/self/fd/N to preserve no-follow semantics.

